answers.body_markdown:
As others pointed out, you return a copy of the list.

1.	Avoid names like `l`: they are very confusing. Use something like `_lst`.
2.	Depending on your purpose you may want to return:
- a copy – the client may modify the copy without changing the `_lst` member: `list &lt;int&gt; getList()`
- a reference – avoids copying and the client may directly modify it: `list &lt;int&gt;&amp; getList()`
- or a constant reference – no copy and the client cannot modify it `_lst`: `const list &lt;int&gt;&amp; getList() const`
3.	If your only intention was to show the content of the list, just add a public member function and remove `getList`: `void dump() const`.
4.	Instead of directly iterating thru `_lst` you may use the `copy` algorithm to copy the content of your list to the console

        void dump()
        {
          copy(_lst.begin(), _lst.end(), std::ostream_iterator&lt;int&gt;(std::cout, &quot;\n&quot;));
        }

5.	Your main becomes:

        int main()
        {
          Algo a;
          a.dump();
        }

